04994nam a22006735i 9780292797475DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212004txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927974757 a10.7560/7029362doi  a(DE-B1597)588626  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aDS135.I713R447 2004 7aBIO0000002bisacsh04a956.7/47004924/0922221 aRejwan, Nissim, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Last Jews in Baghdad :bRemembering a Lost Homeland /cNissim Rejwan. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (268 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword. Jews as Native Iraqis: An Introduction -- tPreface. On Taking Stock -- tChapter 1 In old Baghdad -- tChapter 2 The Rejwan tribe -- tChapter 3 Mother and the placebo effect -- tChapter 4 Na‘ima -- tChapter 5 Early initiations -- tChapter 6 Schooling -- tChapter 7 The great crash and us -- tChapter 8 Hesqail Abul ‘Alwa hires a helper -- tChapter 9 Living in sexual deprivation -- tChapter 10 Idle days -- tChapter 11 Distorted visions -- tChapter 12 Rashid ‘Ali’s coup and its aftermath -- tChapter 13 Bookshop days -- tChapter 14 A deepening friendship -- tChapter 15 The start: movies, book reviews -- tChapter 16 Out in the cold -- tChapter 17 Disposing of a library -- tChapter 18 End of a community -- tChapter 19 Farewells and reunions -- tAppendix A The Jews of Iraq: a brief historical sketch -- tAppendix B A selection of book reviews from the Iraq times -- tIndex of names of persons0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOnce upon a time, Baghdad was home to a flourishing Jewish community. More than a third of the city's people were Jews, and Jewish customs and holidays helped set the pattern of Baghdad's cultural and commercial life. On the city's streets and in the bazaars, Jews, Muslims, and Christians—all native-born Iraqis—intermingled, speaking virtually the same colloquial Arabic and sharing a common sense of national identity. And then, almost overnight it seemed, the state of Israel was born, and lines were drawn between Jews and Arabs. Over the next couple of years, nearly the entire Jewish population of Baghdad fled their Iraqi homeland, never to return. In this beautifully written memoir, Nissim Rejwan recalls the lost Jewish community of Baghdad, in which he was a child and young man from the 1920s through 1951. He paints a minutely detailed picture of growing up in a barely middle-class family, dealing with a motley assortment of neighbors and landlords, struggling through the local schools, and finally discovering the pleasures of self-education and sexual awakening. Rejwan intertwines his personal story with the story of the cultural renaissance that was flowering in Baghdad during the years of his young manhood, describing how his work as a bookshop manager and a staff writer for the Iraq Times brought him friendships with many of the country's leading intellectual and literary figures. He rounds off his story by remembering how the political and cultural upheavals that accompanied the founding of Israel, as well as broad hints sent back by the first arrivals in the new state, left him with a deep ambivalence as he bid a last farewell to a homeland that had become hostile to its native Jews.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aJewszIraqzBaghdadvBiography. 0aJewszIraqzBaghdadxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aJewszIraqzBaghdadxSocial life and customs. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aBeinin, Joel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeinin, Joel.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292797475